  <span id="freeText2270061505680741755" style="display:none">Three words: FAB - U - LOUS! So much to love in this multi-genre book--part historical fiction and cultural; part murder mystery/psychological thriller, all my favorites and quite sensational.<br /><br />It is 1953 in Stalin's Russia and there's a serial killer on the loose. Only that cannot be; Stalin's Russia boasts of being crime free. Therefore, when Leo of the MGB (later known as the KGB) is sent to a colleague's home to investigate the murder of his son, it is not to investigate at all but to sweep it under the rug, to convince the family it was an accidental death. Still, despite not admitting to any real crimes existing, the MGB fabricates all sorts of accusations of spying by ordinary citizens (one of which is Leo's wife), looking at someone the wrong way, etc., and will go to great efforts to prove these innocent people guilty. Everyone is guilty until proven innocent, but no one is ever proven innocent and consequences are paid in big ways. Trust and hope are major themes.<br /><br />There's a lot of background info and setting up of the plot before the action picks up in the latter half of the book. Have patience. It is going to get oh, so good! Leo became a character I could grow to love as he realized what a farce his job and life were, and that there really was someone out there murdering young people. And as his underground, unauthorized investigation will reveal, 44 known murders fit the killer's modus operandi.<br /><br />Who to trust turns out to be NO ONE. Even friends and family have ulterior motives for their actions. A great depiction of life, really survival, in the USSR in those times, with many twists.</span>
